                           </table><center>  						<!--#beginContent#-->
  						<table align='center' cellpadding=5 width='85%'>  <tr><td class='spti2' width='100%'>PLAYER STRATEGY - ENCHANTER</td></tr>  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'><font class='dbti'>CREATION AND HUNTING 1-4 IN TOXX</font> - <small>Darniaq, Xev</td></tr>
  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'>Written on September 6, 2001.
<BR>
<BR>
CREATION NOTE ON RELIGION<BR>
Even before hunting, it should be known your best religion option is Agnostic. I started my Enchanter over because I didn't go this route and was warned by many elders that this would prevent parts of my epic and other quests from being completed. While the 'Illusion' line does help with faction, the religious faction is a separate line. Even if you look like a troll, if you follow anything BUT Agnostic, you will be KoS where you otherwise wouldn't be. 
<BR>
<BR>
Erudians start out with the highest possible Intelligence, so put 25 points into that to bring to 142 and the remaining 5 into Charisma. But, they are also night blind so until you can cast 'Illusion: Half Elf,' pump the Gamma (Options>Display) to max and turn the brightness up on your monitor. This'll help straight away but not alot. For this reason, I recommend NOT playing in Windowed Mode if you can help it, because the relative brightness of the status bars and other nonsense makes the darkness that much more dark. I play in Fullscreen mode.
<BR>
<BR>
STARTING OUT<BR>
You've all heard right, Toxxulia Forest is a tough (or terrible) newbie zone for Erudians first starting out. Most things con red and yellow even close to the guards, and spawn cycle is really short between low-end Kobold Runts (white at 1, low blue at 2) and Scouts (some yellow even at 3). You can try to get into Paineel's newbie zone, but that's a long run if you don't have Spirit of Wolf cast on you (or running with a Bard :o) through a variety of higher level mobs than you are. You can also hop the boat to Qeynos and hunt in their newbie zone, but I don't know if you are immediately KoS with the Half Elves and humans there, and I prefer to fight early on in a less crowded zone anyway.
<BR>
<BR>
You'll start out in Erudin by the town sign with:<BR>
1 Dagger<BR>
5 Food/Drink<BR>
1 Candle<BR>
1 Shallow Breath spell (4 dmg + DoT)<BR>
1 Minor Shielding spell scroll (self-only AC and HP buff)<BR>
1 'a tattered note'
<BR>
<BR>
So obviously you want to arm the dagger and candle (you're night blind), scribe scrolls, memorize both spells and find the guild master (remember to be in windowed mode to read to whom the note goes by right-clicking). He's on the second floor of the Erudin Palace, so just head passed the sign, up the stairs, and walk into the shimmering blue platform on top of a little platform. Find the enchanter guild (yellow flag, named something like 'Craftpeople of Erudin') and go to the second floor to give the tattered note to the Guildmaster. Note that the Magician guild 'Gatecallers of Erudin' will be where you visit at level 4 for the Gate spell and maybe the Reclaim Energy spell.
<BR>
<BR>
Make your way back out to Toxx (pretty much back the way you came and when you see where you started, go to the left and down a set of stairs to another outside area with Paladin and other resources) but feel free to /ooc for directions.
<BR>
<BR>
FIRST ROUND OF HUNTING<BR>
Once in Toxx, the key is to loot EVERYTHING and sell it to the vendor in the hut just southwest of the guard pavilion (entrance to Erudin).
<BR>
<BR> 
1. If you see monsters suspended in mid-air, do NOT attack unless with someone at level 1. There are always TWO mobs together, but you can't target each separately to Lull one (provided you could afford that spell straight away).
<BR>
<BR>
2. You run slow. Don't get damaged below 40% health and expect to make it back to the guards.
<BR>
<BR>
3. It's easy to get lost. Stay within size of the Guard Pavilion and that hut so you can learn the bearings.
<BR>
<BR>
4. Assign 'Sense Heading' to a hotkey. This is a life-saver as it works much faster than /loc and looking at a map.
<BR>
<BR>
5. I pulled with Shallow Breath and then just kept trying to recast it while piercing with the dagger (helps to work skills like Defense, Offense, Piercing (which I always swap out for 2H Blunt) and Channeling).
<BR>
<BR>
6. If you hit level 2 before buying new spells, you can kill a Fire Eye Beetle for their Fire Eye, which gives you limited-ranged Infravision. This helps a great deal, but not enough to lower Gamma or brightness setting.
<BR>
<BR>
7. The minute you have a bit over 3 gold, go back into Erudin Palace. This'll take some time but two things to remember:
<BR>
<BR>
BUYING FIRST SET OF SPELLS
<BR>
On the first floor of the Enchanter guildhall, there is a vendor to the left of the Guildmaster standing there (not the one the note goes to but which can train you later) and buy:
<BR>
<BR> 
Weaken- Target STR debuff<BR>
Strengthen- Self and Target Strengthen<BR>
Pendril's Animation (the last is out of level order but is on this vendor)- Enchanter Pet. Keep in mind, you can NOT control the actions of the pet and it will only enter battle when you take damage from a monster. It will not back off from that battle until the monster is dead (or you cast Reclaim Energy... more on that later).
<BR>
<BR>
Then, go upstairs to the vendor in roughly the same position and buy a stack (probably around 1 gold or so) of 'Tiny Daggers.' NOT Throwing or regular Daggers, nor Bronze Tantos or anything else. Make sure you confirm they are 'Tiny Daggers' as this is your spell component for Pendril's and all further Animations.
<BR>
<BR>
Scribe and memorize, or walk back outside to Toxx and scribe (I prefer being where people may want to talk while resting :) ).
<BR>
<BR>
SECOND ROUND OF HUNTING<BR>
Now you're ready for the first taste of being an Enchanter! Back out in Toxx, cast Pendril's Animation, cast Strengthen on yourself and on the pet it and and Minor Shielding on yourself. Meditate until full of mana. The buffs last a pretty good while. This is my strategy:
<BR>
<BR>
1. Still stay within sight of the guards or hut for bearings and if only high level 2 or low 3.<BR>
2. Pull a white conning monster with the Weaken spell (you will not be able to beat yellows alone)<BR>
3. Let it hit you (or in case of the skunk, Disease you) and your pet will attack.<BR>
4. Go in an tank, and back off if you get below 40%. The pet has almost no HPs and will survive one, maybe two direct hits from the monster. The monster will always aggro on you but won't follow if you back off.<BR>
5. All the while, keep casting Shallow Breath as it amounts to your only DD spell at this point. The best battles at this level are the ones that end the quickest.<BR>
6. Return to the Guards for healing and medding.<BR>
<BR>
One things to consider:<BR>
1. Many people are coming through this zone to visit Warrens and Stonebrunt Mountains. Sometimes they'll hang around buffing and healing newbies, but occasionally you'll find someone who wants to learn the Erudian Language. At level 1 I was payed 8plat to continually spam a guy who wanted to learn it. It worked real well and financed all spells through 1 and 4, along with an Senior Apprentice Robe (+2 mana), a Great Worn Staff, and a few other goodies. You can set up a Socials macro with a /tell command in it so that you don't spam the whole zone :). You can assign that Social macro to a hotkey so you can just keep pressing it, or toggle back and forth between that and Sense Heading, as I recommend. The social macro would look something like this:
<BR>
<BR>
Line 1- /language 2<BR>
Line 2- /pause 5<BR>
Line 3- /tell [playername] I'm trying to teach you Erudian<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Make a second socials macro to switch back to Common  ('/language 1') in case you want to talk to them or anyone else. You have a LOT of downtime while healing and medding, so better to put that to good use if you're not doing other things.
<BR>
<BR>
2. Kobolds will sometimes drop backpacks, boxes and bags, so don't waste hard earned money buying these. Just keep selling when your inventory gets full.
<BR>
<BR>
BUYING SECOND SET OF SPELLS<BR>
Once you've got a few more gold (from selling loot too) buy Lull. If two of the same monster are near eachother, they'll both come to you if you pull one. Casting this on the one that is farther away (NOT the closer one) will allow you to only pull one at a time.
<BR>
<BR>
Three more to consider but aren't required:
<BR>
<BR>
1. Reclaim Energy- gives you back some mana and dispels your pet. This is good if you're afraid your pet will run off after a fleeing monster, only to return with 20 of his closest friends.<BR>
2. Minor Illusion- this is a fun spell, but unless you plan on sitting in the middle of the forest while healing and meditating, it's really only just fun. What is nice is that your pet will not disappear on you in this form.<BR>
3. I prefer a 2H blunt weapon to the piercing one we start with. Skeletons especially drop faster against blunt than pierce (not much to pierce :) ), and while the delay is high, the damage output is worth it, especially with your pet. I bought a Great Worn Staff (I think 7dmg, 40delay) for around 1plat.
<BR>
<BR>
THIRD ROUND OF HUNTING<BR>
Keep going until level 4. Life really begins for an Enchanter at this point, but in three characters I've only gotten this far. My first attempt long ago was in Greater Faydark, but I liked the Magician pet better at the time (and have since grown bored and frustrated with him at 24). My second attempt I made the mistake of choosing the Quellious religion, and by the third time, I hit level 3 again in two hours :)
<BR>
<BR>
At level 4, I would suggest getting outta dodge and heading over to the Qeynos Hills to hunt Gnolls. Make sure you get bound outside of Qeynos, as you can't bind yet and don't want to end up in Toxxulia with your corpse near Blackburrow. There is a stacking quest there (Gnolls Fangs to Captain Tillin in Warrior Guild behind the PvP arena [you can walk around it] of South Qeynos and then the resultant Moonstone to MacNeal in the Fish's Ale near the docks in the same town). Great exp and potential loot, but fangs are NO DROP.
<BR>
<BR>
I was luckily able to afford all the spells straight away, but the second time around I won't be able to (unless I get lucky again :), so I suspect my purchase order to be:
<BR>
<BR>
1. Juli's Animation<BR>
2. Tashan- This lowers the magic resistance of the monster, best to cast this first and perhaps pull with it so that Fear and spells will hold.<BR>
3. Haze- Targetable AC buff, makes you harder to be hit<BR>
4. Mezzmerize- THE class-defining spell. Sort of a stun but it lasts a good amount of time to help separate monsters that are coming in together.<BR>
5. Fear- the OTHER spell that begins to show the power of the Enchanter. This will force the mob to flee. Remember your pet will continue bashing at it until dead and may follow it a long ways ;)<BR>
6. Suffocating Sphere- DD/DoT upgrade to Shallow Breath<BR>
7. Enfeeblement- Upgrade to Weaken<BR>
8. Invisibility- For obvious reasons, purchased from the Magician guild I think.<BR>
9. Gate- Returns you to your bind point.<BR>
10. Illusion: Half Elf- For faction upgrade in Qeynos<BR>
11. Color Flux- area of effect (AoE) stun, radiating from you<BR></td></tr>
  <tr><td class='db'>&nbsp;</td></tr>
